 only to discern the differentiating features of the phenomena to be understood, but also to orient us to the various meaning contexts that can frame their interpretation. Makkreel develops overlooked resources of Kant’s transcendental thought in order to reconceive hermeneutics as a critical inquiry into the appropriate contextual conditions of understanding and interpretation. He shows that a crucial task of hermeneutical critique is to establish priorities among the contexts that may be brought to bear on the interpretation of history and culture. The final chapter turns to the contemporary art scene and explores how orientational contexts can be reconfigured to respond to the ways in which media of communication are being transformed by digital technology. Altogether, Makkreel offers a promising way of thinking about the shifting contexts that we bring to bear on interpretations of all kinds, whether of texts, art works, or the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHermeneutics. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  ahermeneutics, philosophy, orientation, judgement, reflection, interpretation, kant, art, technology, aesthetics, heidegger, cognition, expression, inexpressible, representational signs, context, nonfiction, adjudication, legitimacy, meaning, emulation, truth, opinion, belief, dilthey, ontology, history, time, nietzsche, narrative, universalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022624931540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226249452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226249452/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles